Wealthier, means healthier?

A baby born today may live double the life span than one born half a century ago.


Over the past decades, people have been living longer almost everywhere. But while some countries experienced more rapid growth in life expectancy, others advanced much more slowly. Meanwhile, global economies have also been expanding at a dramatic pace. This raises a simple but interesting question: does being richer help people live longer, healthier lives?

Have you ever wondered the same question? If so


The interactive worldmap and plot below explore how economic growth may (or may not) link to longer life expectancy between 1952 - 2007.

Although many previous studies have reported a clear link, real life is rarely straightforward. As you could probably see yourself, economic growths doesnt necessarily bring us longevity. However, due to many complicating factors (education status, political stability, healthcare accessand thats only the beginning of the list) contributing to lifespan, it has always been difficult to decipher which factor is increasing it. If you come across any articles claiming that X makes you live longer!, take a minute to pause and ask yourself: what else might be playing a role here?
